<h2>North Dakota Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>North Dakota homeowners have access to several valuable incentives and rebates that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC installations. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, before stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, making it one of the most valuable incentives available to North Dakota residents.</p>

<p>The state offers a Renewable Energy Tax Credit that provides additional savings for qualifying renewable energy systems, including solar installations. This credit can be worth up to \$3,000 for residential installations, further reducing the net cost of solar systems. North Dakota also exempts renewable energy systems from property tax assessments, meaning the added home value from solar installations won't increase property taxes. Additionally, the state provides sales tax exemptions for solar equipment, reducing upfront costs.</p>

<p>Xcel Energy, serving much of North Dakota, offers net metering programs that allow solar customers to receive credit for excess electricity generated by their systems. The utility also provides rebates for energy-efficient HVAC equipment, including up to \$800 for qualifying high-efficiency heat pumps and up to \$400 for ENERGY STAR certified air conditioning systems. Many local utilities throughout the state offer similar programs, and some provide additional rebates for smart thermostats and ductless mini-split systems.</p>

<p>The Database of State Incentives for Renewables & Efficiency (DSIRE) maintains current information on all available incentives in North Dakota. Many HVAC installations also qualify for federal tax credits, particularly geothermal heat pumps, which are eligible for a 30% federal tax credit similar to solar systems. Local utility programs may offer additional rebates for comprehensive energy efficiency upgrades that combine solar and high-efficiency HVAC systems.</p>

